04255nam a22009615i 9780520934368DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20082007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696358  a97805209343687 a10.1525/97805209343682doi  a(DE-B1597)520656  a(OCoLC)609850127  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBD581 4aBD581 .S377 2007 7aPHI0020002bisacsh04a1801 aSedley, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCreationism and Its Critics in Antiquity /cDavid Sedley. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSather Classical Lectures ;v660 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe world is configured in ways that seem systematically hospitable to life forms, especially the human race. Is this the outcome of divine planning or simply of the laws of physics? Ancient Greeks and Romans famously disagreed on whether the cosmos was the product of design or accident. In this book, David Sedley examines this question and illuminates new historical perspectives on the pantheon of thinkers who laid the foundations of Western philosophy and science. Versions of what we call the "creationist" option were widely favored by the major thinkers of classical antiquity, including Plato, whose ideas on the subject prepared the ground for Aristotle's celebrated teleology. But Aristotle aligned himself with the anti-creationist lobby, whose most militant members—the atomists—sought to show how a world just like ours would form inevitably by sheer accident, given only the infinity of space and matter. This stimulating study explores seven major thinkers and philosophical movements enmeshed in the debate: Anaxagoras, Empedocles, Socrates, Plato, the atomists, Aristotle, and the Stoics.  aMode of access: Internet via W